ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: ENACT01 Behavior - Engages in other activities (e.g. answers door or mobile, completes paperwork)
ENACT01 Behavior - Laughs at client
ENACT01 Behavior - Negative facial expression or other negative physical behavior
ENACT01 Behavior - Has not minimized inappropriate distractions (eg, turn off pop-ups, turn off phone notifications)
ENACT01 Behavior - Allows for silences
ENACT01 Behavior - Maintains appropriate eye contact through video image (eg, looking in general direction of client)
ENACT01 Behavior - Continuously uses supportive body language (head nod) and utterances (uh huh)
ENACT01 Behavior - Sets up clear visibility (eg, no backlight, head in frame)
ENACT01 Behavior - Helps client set up audio/video for clear communication in a supportive manner
ENACT01 Behavior - Checks with client to make sure helper's audio can easily and clearly be heard
ENACT01 Behavior - Confirms plan if call gets disconnected (eg. try on the same line, call in 5 min, etc)
ENACT01 Behavior - Varies body language during the session in relation to client's content and expressions
ENACT01 Non-Verbal Communication & Active Listening -  Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT02 Behavior - Interrupts client
ENACT02 Behavior - Asks many suggestive or leading closed-ended questions (eg, You didn't really want to do that, right?)
ENACT02 Behavior - Corrects client (what you really mean...)  or Uses accusatory statements (you shouldn't have said that to your husband)
ENACT02 Behavior - Uses culturally and age inappropriate language and terms
ENACT02 Behavior - Open ended questions
ENACT02 Behavior - Summarizing or paraphrasing statements
ENACT02 Behavior - Allows client to complete statements before responding
ENACT02 Behavior - Encourages client to continue explaining (tell me more about...)
ENACT02 Behavior - Uses clarifying statements in first person (I heard you say, I understood...)
ENACT02 Behavior - Matches rhythm to client's, allowing longer or shorter pauses based on client
ENACT02 Verbal Communication Skills - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT03 Behavior - Forces client to disclose to helper or others
ENACT03 Behavior - Describes confidentiality inaccurately (eg, I will only tell your family)
ENACT03 Behavior - Promises all things will be kept confidential without exceptions
ENACT03 Behavior - Minimizes client's concerns about confienditality (eg, it doesn't matter if anyone else hears us)
ENACT03 Behavior - Explains concept of confidentiality
ENACT03 Behavior - Addresses confidentiality issues specific to remote communication (eg, family overhearing)
ENACT03 Behavior - Lists exceptions for breaking confidentiality for self-harm or harm to others
ENACT03 Behavior - Explains why it can be important to break confidentiality
ENACT03 Behavior - Details the referral process related to confidentiality and exceptions
ENACT03 Behavior - Asks questions to assess client's understanding of confidentiality
ENACT03 Behavior - Helps client achieve comfortable level of privacy (eg, separate room, using headphones)
ENACT03 Behavior - Creates a "code word" with client in case client needs to stop
ENACT03 Explanation and Promotopm of Confidentiality - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT04 Behavior - Dominates session describing a personal experience
ENACT04 Behavior - Minimizes client's problems by describing how the helper has dealt with this
ENACT04 Behavior - Asking unnecessary embarrassing personal questions
ENACT04 Behavior - Discusses confidential information of other clients
ENACT04 Behavior - Introduces self and explains role
ENACT04 Behavior - Makes casual, informal conversation
ENACT04 Behavior - Asks for client's introduction, eg, what client prefers to be called
ENACT04 Behavior - Shares general experience to relate to the client (eg, about one's community/region)
ENACT04 Behavior - Asks client's reflection related to helper's information that is shared
ENACT04 Behavior - Checks with client that they are comfortable (eg, preferred language, has a drink of water ready)
ENACT 04 Rapport Building and Self-Disclosure - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT05 Behavior - Makes statements that client's response is unusual or atypical for others in similar situations (eg, people don't usually react this way)
ENACT05 Behavior - Minimizes or dismisses client's feelings or emotions
ENACT05 Behavior - Forces client to describe emotions
ENACT05 Behavior - Appropriately encourages client to share feelings
ENACT05 Behavior - Explain that others may share similar symptoms, reactions, and concerns, given similar experiences
ENACT05 Behavior - Asks client to reflect on the experience of sharing emotions
ENACT05 Behavior - Explores potential reasons for hesitance to share emotions
ENACT05 Behavior - Comments thoughtfully on client's facial expression to encourage emotional expression
ENACT05 Behavior - Validates emotional responses while also reframing potential harmful emotional reactions
ENACT05 Exploration and Normalization of Feelings - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT06 Behavior - Critical of client's concerns
ENACT06 Behavior - Dismissive of client's concerns
ENACT06 Behavior - Helper's emotional response appears inappropriate, fake or acting
ENACT06 Behavior - Is warm, friendly, and genuine throughout session
ENACT06 Behavior - Continuously shows concern or care for the client (eg, That sounds sad, can you tell me more about it?)
ENACT06 Behavior - Asks question to identify what emotions the client was feeling (eg, I wonder if you felt sad or angry when this happened)
ENACT06 Behavior - Asks client to reflect on empathic statements from helper (eg, What did you think when I said you sounded sad?)
ENACT06 Demonstration of Empaty, Warmth and Genuineness - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT07 Behavior - Does not ask about self-harm
ENACT07 Behavior - Lectures client with religious or legal reasons against self-harm (eg, this is sin, or this is against the law)
ENACT07 Behavior - Expresses disbelief when client discusses harm (eg, accuses client of discussing self-harm to get attention; states that others would not actually harm client or client's children)
ENACT07 Behavior - Encourages client not tell anyone else about self-harm or harm to others
ENACT07 Behavior - Asks about self-harm or harm to others, or explores harm if raised by client
ENACT07 Behavior - Asks about current intent, means, or prior attempts
ENACT07 Behavior - Asks about risk and/or protective factors
ENACT07 Behavior - If current risk is low or high, helps client to develop safety plan (eg, coping strategies and help seeking)
ENACT07 Behavior - Asks where client is located and access to in-person resources (e.g., "If you didn’t feel safe, where is the nearest medical facility you could go for help?")
ENACT07 Behavior - Offers local hotline or other remote referral resources in case of emergency (eg, 'If you have an emergency, you can call x')
ENACT07 Assessment of Harm to Self, Harm to Others, Harm From Others and Developing Collaborative Response Plan - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT08 Behavior - Criticises client for letting symptoms impact functioning (eg, you are weak, you have no willpower)
ENACT08 Behavior - Tells client there is no relation between mental health concerns and daily functioning or does not ask about how mental health is affecting daily functioning
ENACT08 Behavior - Criticizes client for impact of her/his problems on children, spouse, or family members
ENACT08 Behavior - Makes client feel guilty for impact on children, family, and others
ENACT08 Behavior - Asks about daily functioning
ENACT08 Behavior - Asks about connection between daily functioning and mental health
ENACT08 Behavior - Clarifies and/or supports clients' connections between functioning and mental health or reframes as needed
ENACT08 Behavior - Explores relationship in both directions (daily life to symptoms; symptoms to daily life)
ENACT08 Behavior - Asks about history of daily functioning compared to current social context (eg, COVID19;how long has this been going on?)
ENACT08 Connection to Social Functioning and Impact on Life - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT09 Behavior - Criticizes client's view of problem as ignorant, superstitious, etc.
ENACT09 Behavior - Endorses harmful beliefs of client or social network
ENACT09 Behavior - Asks about client's view on cause of problem
ENACT09 Behavior - Asks about family's or social support network's view on cause of problem
ENACT09 Behavior - Incorporates client's perspective of cause in care planning and goal setting in non-harmful manner
ENACT09 Behavior - Discusses alternative to harmful explanations (eg, You said this was because you failed your family, I wonder if there is another way to think about this situation?)
ENACT09 Behavior - Addresses differences in client's view of cause and support network's view of cause
ENACT09 Exploration of Client's and Social Support Network's Explanation for Problem (Causal and Explanatory Models) - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT10 Behavior - Tells client not to involve family or close person in any way during treatment or recovery
ENACT10 Behavior - Forces client to involve family or close person in treatment process
ENACT10 Behavior - Demands to speak with family or close person without permission from client
ENACT10 Behavior - Allows an accompanying close person to disempower the client.
ENACT10 Behavior - Asks about close person(s) in client's life (eg, household members, family, or other)
ENACT10 Behavior - Asks client how they would like to involve close person(s) in the care process
ENACT10 Behavior - Asks client who they live with
ENACT10 Behavior - Explores client choices or reasons for involving or not involving close, familiar person
ENACT10 Behavior - Does role-play or discusses options for successful interaction with close person (eg, helper plays role of family member)
ENACT10 - Appropriate Involvement of Family Members and Relevant Others - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT11 Behavior - Tells client that his/her goals (expectations) can't be met, but doesn't give a reason
ENACT11 Behavior - Gives incorrect, misleading, or unrealistic information about treatment goals
ENACT11 Behavior - Dictates goal for client (forces goal upon client)
ENACT11 Behavior - Asks client about goals (expectations)
ENACT11 Behavior - Clearly explains how client's goals and expectations fit with treatment plan
ENACT11 Behavior - Prioritization and modification of treatment plan to fit client goals (expectations)
ENACT11 Behavior - Works with client to reframe their goals within scope of the treatment plan (eg, Your goal is to get a job, could we work together on a goal that will help you do that?)
ENACT11 Collaborative Goal Setting and Addressing Client's Expectations - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT12 Behavior - Makes negative statements about client's doubts (how do you expect to get better if you have no hope...)
ENACT12 Behavior - Gives unrealistic expectations (everything will be cured or solved...)
ENACT12 Behavior - Provides no hope for change (this problem cannot be solved...)
ENACT12 Behavior - Explains how client can be hopeful about possibility of change
ENACT12 Behavior - Praises client for seeking care
ENACT12 Behavior - Solicits and explores client's doubt about the treatment
ENACT12 Behavior - Helper shares reasons for hope based on helper's prior experience or client's behaviours
ENACT12 Behavior - Discusses reasons for hope when client is doubtful or dissatisfied
ENACT12 Promotion of Realistic Hope for Change - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT13 Behavior - Makes negative statements about client's coping mechanisms (that would never work...)
ENACT13 Behavior - Encourages or shows acceptance of harmful coping mechanisms
ENACT13 Behavior - Asks client about current or past coping mechanisms (how s/he keeps going after the problem started...)
ENACT13 Behavior - Praises client for positive or safe current or prior solutions
ENACT13 Behavior - Encourages use of continued positive coping mechanisms
ENACT13 Behavior - Reflection on prior unhealthy strategies and brainstorm positive alternatives
ENACT13 Incorporation of Coping Mechanisms and Prior Solutions - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT14 Behavior - Uses technical terms without checking client's understanding
ENACT14 Behavior - Uses stigmatizing mental health terms
ENACT14 Behavior - Conducts accurate psychoeducation using simple terms
ENACT14 Behavior - Includes local concepts and terminology into psychoeducation
ENACT14 Behavior - Incorporates client's description of the problem
ENACT14 Behavior - Checks that client understands psychoeducation
ENACT14 Psychoeducation and Use of Local Terminology - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT15 Behavior - Lectures client about what to do without asking for client feedback
ENACT15 Behavior - Offers negative or harmful suggestions
ENACT15 Behavior - Asks for feedback from client to see if any offered suggestions are helpful
ENACT15 Behavior - Provides clarifications, reframing, or alternative suggestions based on feedback
ENACT15 Behavior - Summarizes feedback provided by client and checks if interpretation is correct
ENACT15 Elicitation of Feedback When Providing Advice, Suggestions and Recommendations - Rating Level
Notes: 1 = unhelpful; 2 = some basic skills; 3 = all basic skills; 4 = advanced skills

ElementDescription: ENACT01 Behavior - Inappropriate physical contact
ENACT01 Behavior - Maintains open posture (body toward client)
ENACT03 Behavior - Topics of discussion are appropriate to confidentiality of setting
